"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody. A key concept in understanding the decay cycle when looking at soil, when looking at your agricultural, uh looking at your gardening, is to understand digestion. So your soil is a living entity and you are feeding it organic matter which it is breaking down. Now, if you have a very rough soil uh organic matter, like say a wood chip, you're gonna see ants and things that cut and break, you're gonna see large beetles. And if you have a finer mix, you're gonna see more earthworms and small beetles and little crawly things you can't quite identify, but the whole soil will look living in terms of the amount that's going on as that gets digested, you'll see less and less of that large uh element, the large insect breaking things down. You'll see more and or you won't see it because it'll be too small, but there'll be more and more microscopic action going on. And this is what feeds the plants. So you want the soil to break down in this way. And knowing that the soil is digesting the matter is key because it digestion is not a thing, it's not A or B, it's a whole spectrum. Do you have a heavy digestion? Do you have a light digestion? What is the organic material in there and how much biological life is feeding off that? If you have good digestible organic matter, the biology just comes naturally. You know, the microbes just float in on dust, and then they when they find a good home, they they replicate at exponential rates, so they quickly fill the environments that they have if it's a fertile environment. So when you add the good organic matter, you increase the digestion. Now, this happens over a period of time because you can't just dump a bunch of organic material on there. You have to make it and they have to spread it around. You don't put much on all at once forever. So you just layer it in and then you create cycles that replenish the organic matter as you grow out of it. And so not only are you adding more organic matter, but you're creating a cycle that keeps it inside, keeps it there once you've added it. And this digestion rate is how you can measure the biological activity in your soil, the fertility of your soil. And it's a really cool thing to check out. Like in my yard where I don't grow, it's surrounded by the compost pile, the worm pile, and then my garden. So there's these islands of fertility. And what's being connected between it, I've noticed in the past uh year, I've been working on myself for about three years, uh, there's a heavy worm population. So like the area between my fertilities, uh fertility patches is becoming more fertile. It's beginning to link the two together with earthworms, which means that the organic matter is getting processed in the soil. And I have chickens and dogs and uh uh a lot of everything's being left on the ground, and I mulch my grass. I'm also letting it go to wild grass, legumes and other things. So like there's this whole digestion that's happening. It's so active now that I'll see some chicken poo one day and like two days later it's gone. Anyway, just want to make a video about digestion. Thanks.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 2.16,\n      \"end\": 3.44,\n      \"duration\": 1.28,\n      \"confidence\": 0.985,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\": 2.16,\n          \"end\": 2.48,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.994\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 2.64,\n          \"end\": 2.88,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 2.88,\n          \"end\": 3.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 3.04,\n          \"end\": 3.2,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n      